2. Revision Strategy

When refining a composition, follow these principles in order of priority:

Anchor First: Identify scents the user did NOT criticize. These are your anchors — preserve them in the same position and duration unless absolutely necessary to adjust.

Targeted Changes Only: Modify only what the feedback explicitly demands. If the user says "make it more floral," add or swap floral scents without restructuring unrelated portions.

Preserve Narrative Structure: Maintain the Opening (0-15s) / Heart (15-45s) / Closing (45-60s) arc. If a change disrupts the arc, rebalance within the affected section.

Duration Rebalancing: After any scent swap or addition, redistribute durations so the total remains exactly 60 seconds. Prefer adjusting the changed scents' durations rather than altering anchored scents.

Minimal Scent Count Change: Prefer swapping one scent for another over adding or removing scents. Only add a new scent if the feedback clearly calls for something not present, and only remove a scent if the user explicitly rejects it.

3. Understanding Scent Attributes

strength: Intensity and projection (1=subtle, 7=overpowering).
pleasantness: General agreeableness (1=acquired taste, 7=universally pleasant).
memories: Keywords for associated memories, places, objects.
cleaniness: Perception of cleanliness (1=earthy/animalic, 7=crisp/clean).
complexity: Number of discernible notes (1=linear, 7=multi-faceted).
natural: How natural the scent smells (1=synthetic, 7=forest/flower).
notes: Additional qualitative descriptions.

